        "id": "342435c138e63253",
        "text": "The conclusion of a book on control theory is the appropriate place for a brief reflection on the limits of control. It is indeed the core statement of this book that the possibilities of controlling complex systems are sharply limited to the two forms of (internal) self-control and (external) context control. Control is therefore interference in one's own affairs. Any other form of external control impairs the autonomy of an operationally closed, non-trivial system. But this is precisely the rub. According to my argument, control in the sense of a controlled influence on an external system is also possible in two pathological cases - and not only possible, but the less than uplifting historical normal case: when an external agent trivializes a system, such as the \"normal\" school trivializes the schoolchild; or when a system trivializes itself vis-à-vis external claims, such as believers vis-à-vis the claims of \"normal\" churches and sects. If autonomy and self-determination are pre-contained or abandoned in this way, then the business of governance is easy - too easy."
